1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,279
Have you ever wondered why generating text

2
00:00:03,279 --> 00:00:06,559
with large language models feels so sluggish?

3
00:00:06,559 --> 00:00:09,838
A seventy-billion parameter model seems to crawl,

4
00:00:09,838 --> 00:00:13,118
outputting just a few words per second.

5
00:00:13,118 --> 00:00:17,803
You might think the GPU is working at full capacity,

6
00:00:17,803 --> 00:00:20,145
burning through complex mathematical equations.

7
00:00:20,145 --> 00:00:24,362
But the truth is, the GPU is actually idling.

8
00:00:24,362 --> 00:00:27,641
It is trapped behind a physical barrier

9
00:00:27,641 --> 00:00:30,452
known as the memory bandwidth bottleneck.

10
00:00:30,452 --> 00:00:34,200
Today, we will explore Speculative Decoding: the brilliant,

11
00:00:34,200 --> 00:00:37,479
mathematically rigorous algorithm that breaks this bottleneck

12
00:00:37,479 --> 00:00:42,164
to speed up LLM inference by two to three times,

13
00:00:42,164 --> 00:00:44,975
with absolutely zero loss in quality.

14
00:00:44,975 --> 00:00:47,809
To understand why LLMs are slow,

15
00:00:47,809 --> 00:00:51,115
we have to look at arithmetic intensity.

16
00:00:51,115 --> 00:00:55,366
In standard autoregressive generation, a model produces text token-by-token.

17
00:00:55,366 --> 00:00:57,728
To generate a single token,

18
00:00:57,728 --> 00:01:01,034
the GPU must load every single parameter

19
00:01:01,034 --> 00:01:04,340
of the model from High Bandwidth Memory,

20
00:01:04,340 --> 00:01:08,118
or HBM, into the fast on-chip SRAM cache.

21
00:01:08,118 --> 00:01:10,480
For a seventy-billion parameter model,

22
00:01:10,480 --> 00:01:13,786
that means transferring one hundred and forty

23
00:01:13,786 --> 00:01:17,092
gigabytes of data across the memory bus

24
00:01:17,092 --> 00:01:19,926
just to calculate a single word.

25
00:01:19,926 --> 00:01:23,232
Because memory transfer is orders of magnitude

26
00:01:23,232 --> 00:01:26,538
slower than arithmetic computation, the GPU cores

27
00:01:26,538 --> 00:01:30,789
spend over ninety percent of their time sitting idle,

28
00:01:30,789 --> 00:01:32,206
waiting for data.

29
00:01:32,206 --> 00:01:35,040
Standard generation is completely memory-bandwidth bound.

30
00:01:35,039 --> 00:01:37,881
How do we solve a physical hardware

31
00:01:37,881 --> 00:01:40,317
bottleneck with a clever software algorithm?

32
00:01:40,317 --> 00:01:42,347
The answer is Speculative Decoding.

33
00:01:42,347 --> 00:01:46,001
Imagine you need to write a highly technical report.

34
00:01:46,001 --> 00:01:49,655
Instead of having a senior researcher draft it word-by-word,

35
00:01:49,655 --> 00:01:53,715
you hire a fast junior writer to draft several paragraphs.

36
00:01:53,715 --> 00:01:57,774
The senior researcher then reviews the draft in a single,

37
00:01:57,774 --> 00:02:02,240
swift sweep, correcting any mistakes, but accepting everything that looks correct.

38
00:02:02,240 --> 00:02:05,488
In the AI world, we use a tiny,

39
00:02:05,488 --> 00:02:08,736
fast draft model to speculate several candidate tokens,

40
00:02:08,736 --> 00:02:11,578
and a large, slow target model to

41
00:02:11,578 --> 00:02:13,607
verify them all in parallel.

42
00:02:13,608 --> 00:02:17,190
Here is how the collaboration works in detail.

43
00:02:17,190 --> 00:02:22,116
First, we run the small draft model autoregressively for K steps.

44
00:02:22,116 --> 00:02:25,698
Because the draft model has far fewer parameters,

45
00:02:25,698 --> 00:02:30,624
it can load its weights and generate candidate tokens extremely quickly.

46
00:02:30,624 --> 00:02:33,311
For example, if K equals four,

47
00:02:33,311 --> 00:02:38,237
the draft model rapidly generates four candidate tokens, one after another.

48
00:02:38,237 --> 00:02:40,924
These tokens are cheap to produce,

49
00:02:40,924 --> 00:02:43,610
but they are just educated guesses.

50
00:02:43,610 --> 00:02:47,641
They might contain grammatical errors or misinterpret the prompt,

51
00:02:47,641 --> 00:02:50,328
so they cannot be trusted blindly.

52
00:02:50,328 --> 00:02:52,089
Next comes the masterstroke.

53
00:02:52,089 --> 00:02:55,172
We feed the prompt and all four

54
00:02:55,172 --> 00:02:58,695
draft tokens into the large target model simultaneously.

55
00:02:58,695 --> 00:03:01,778
Normally, running the target model four times

56
00:03:01,778 --> 00:03:04,860
would take four slow memory load cycles.

57
00:03:04,860 --> 00:03:08,383
But because the draft tokens are already written,

58
00:03:08,383 --> 00:03:12,787
we can process them in a single parallel forward pass.

59
00:03:12,787 --> 00:03:15,870
The target model computes the exact probability

60
00:03:15,870 --> 00:03:18,953
distributions for all four positions at once.

61
00:03:18,953 --> 00:03:22,035
We have traded serial memory accesses for

62
00:03:22,035 --> 00:03:26,879
a single parallel computation, fully utilizing the GPU's idle compute cores.

63
00:03:26,879 --> 00:03:29,781
Now, how does the target model decide

64
00:03:29,781 --> 00:03:31,854
which draft tokens to accept?

65
00:03:31,854 --> 00:03:36,000
We cannot just accept tokens where the target model agrees,

66
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:38,901
because that would alter the final probability

67
00:03:38,901 --> 00:03:40,974
distribution and degrade model quality.

68
00:03:40,974 --> 00:03:43,876
Instead, we use a stochastic acceptance algorithm.

69
00:03:43,876 --> 00:03:48,021
For each draft token, we compare the target model's probability,

70
00:03:48,021 --> 00:03:50,923
P, to the draft model's probability, Q.

71
00:03:50,923 --> 00:03:53,825
If the target model's probability is greater

72
00:03:53,825 --> 00:03:58,385
than or equal to the draft model's, we accept the token.

73
00:03:58,385 --> 00:04:01,287
If it is lower, we accept it

74
00:04:01,287 --> 00:04:03,359
stochastically based on their ratio,

75
00:04:03,359 --> 00:04:07,919
keeping the final output mathematically identical to the target model alone.

76
00:04:07,919 --> 00:04:11,160
What happens when a draft token is rejected?

77
00:04:11,160 --> 00:04:13,995
Suppose the first two tokens are accepted,

78
00:04:13,995 --> 00:04:16,020
but the third is rejected.

79
00:04:16,020 --> 00:04:19,260
We immediately discard the third and fourth tokens.

80
00:04:19,260 --> 00:04:22,096
But we do not go home empty-handed.

81
00:04:22,096 --> 00:04:24,931
In the same parallel forward pass where

82
00:04:24,931 --> 00:04:27,361
the target model verified the draft,

83
00:04:27,361 --> 00:04:30,196
it also calculated the true probability distribution

84
00:04:30,196 --> 00:04:33,436
for the next token at the rejection point.

85
00:04:33,436 --> 00:04:36,272
We sample from this corrected distribution to

86
00:04:36,272 --> 00:04:39,917
get a brand new, verified token on the spot.

87
00:04:39,917 --> 00:04:42,752
In this single step, we successfully generated

88
00:04:42,752 --> 00:04:47,207
three verified tokens while only loading the large model's weights once.

89
00:04:47,207 --> 00:04:50,250
Behind the scenes, we also have to

90
00:04:50,250 --> 00:04:54,595
manage the model's memory state: the Key-Value, or KV, cache.

91
00:04:54,595 --> 00:04:57,637
The KV cache stores past key and

92
00:04:57,637 --> 00:05:01,549
value vectors to prevent redundant calculations in future steps.

93
00:05:01,549 --> 00:05:04,156
When the draft model speculates tokens,

94
00:05:04,156 --> 00:05:08,502
both the draft and target models update their KV caches.

95
00:05:08,502 --> 00:05:13,282
But when a rejection occurs, those speculative cache entries become invalid.

96
00:05:13,282 --> 00:05:16,324
The algorithm must dynamically roll back the

97
00:05:16,324 --> 00:05:18,497
KV caches of both models,

98
00:05:18,497 --> 00:05:21,539
pruning the entries corresponding to the discarded

99
00:05:21,539 --> 00:05:24,581
tokens so that the next round of

100
00:05:24,581 --> 00:05:27,623
speculation starts with a perfectly clean history.

101
00:05:27,623 --> 00:05:31,152
The performance impact of speculative decoding is staggering.

102
00:05:31,152 --> 00:05:34,681
In practice, draft models achieve high acceptance rates,

103
00:05:34,681 --> 00:05:38,650
often accepting three to four tokens per draft cycle.

104
00:05:38,650 --> 00:05:41,738
This translates to a direct two to

105
00:05:41,738 --> 00:05:44,384
three times speedup in wall-clock latency.

106
00:05:44,384 --> 00:05:47,913
And because the stochastic verification math is exact,

107
00:05:47,913 --> 00:05:51,000
the output is guaranteed to be identical

108
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:54,088
to what the large target model would

109
00:05:54,088 --> 00:05:56,293
have produced on its own.

110
00:05:56,293 --> 00:05:59,822
It is a pure win: faster response times,

111
00:05:59,822 --> 00:06:03,791
lower hardware costs, and absolutely zero compromise on quality.

112
00:06:03,791 --> 00:06:08,926
Speculative Decoding teaches us a profound lesson about modern artificial intelligence.

113
00:06:08,926 --> 00:06:12,194
We do not always need faster transistors

114
00:06:12,194 --> 00:06:15,461
or bigger chips to build faster systems.

115
00:06:15,461 --> 00:06:18,729
By understanding the physical layout of our

116
00:06:18,729 --> 00:06:22,930
hardware and designing algorithms that align with its strengths,

117
00:06:22,930 --> 00:06:25,731
we can unlock massive performance gains.

118
00:06:25,731 --> 00:06:28,999
If you enjoyed this deep dive into

119
00:06:28,999 --> 00:06:32,266
the engineering of speed, subscribe to Gemini

120
00:06:32,266 --> 00:06:36,001
three point five Flash Model for more insights.

121
00:06:36,001 --> 00:06:41,135
Remember: true optimization isn't just about raw horsepower—it's about working smarter.
